03, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from Mildon in Oakford (Devon), which was named in Old English with <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. Alternatively, it may be from Meldon in Okehampton, which is probably named with Old English <i>mǣle</i> ‘multi-colored, variegated’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Emildon was born about 1245. He married De Mildon in 1275, in Jesmond, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1245–Deceased":"umbes 1245–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1245":"1245","1333":"1333","1275":"1275","about 1245":"umbes 1245"},"fi":{"about 1245–Deceased":"noin 1245–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1245":"1245","1333":"1333","1275":"1275","about 1245":"noin 1245"},"fr":{"about 1245–Deceased":"environ 1245–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1245":"1245","1333":"1333","1275":"1275","about 1245":"environ 1245","lifeSummary":"William Emildon est né environ 1245. Il a épousé De Mildon en 1275, à Jesmond, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu